\begin_layout Subsection
Surface defects as transfer matrices
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Surface defects and L-operators
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now we introduce a half-BPS surface defect, and put it on 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}\times S^{1}\subset S^{3}\times S^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 The first 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

 factor may be taken to be either 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \zeta_{1}=0\right\} $
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \zeta_{2}=0\right\} $
\end_inset

 in the parametrization 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\zeta_{1}\right|^{2}+\left|\zeta_{2}\right|^{2}=1$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 These are the circles in 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{3}$
\end_inset

 that are left invariant under the action of the isometry group 
\begin_inset Formula $U(1)_{p}\times U(1)_{q}$
\end_inset

.
 As explained in section ??, the index in the presence of the surface defect
 is again given by a correlation function os line operators in a 2d TQFT
 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

.
 The correlator now contains a new line operator created by the D3-brane
 ending on the D5-branes, which was denoted by dashed line: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
dashedline.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 This line operator is specified by a representation of SU(N) [Gadde-Gukov,
 Gukov-Witten].
 In fact, it is labeled with a pair of representations 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(R_{1},R_{2}\right)$
\end_inset

 since in general we can take superposition of two surface defects, each
 wrapped around either circle in 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In any case, the correlation function equals the partition function of a
 lattice model whose lattice is made of two kinds of lines, zig-zag paths
 coming from NS5-branes and the dashed line coming from the D3-branes.
 An extra dimension emerges as the M-theory circle if the brane system is
 embedded in the M-theory via T-duality along the second 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{1}$
\end_inset

 factor.
 Under this embedding, the D3-branes are mapped to M2-branes supported at
 points on the M-theory circle.
 Thus, the inclusion of the dashed line does not spoil the integrability
 of the lattice model.
 Moreover, by deforming the zig-zag paths near the dashed line, we can always
 make the neighborhood of the dashed line look like 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
dashedandsolids\label{eq:transferL}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

in some 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(N,q\right)$
\end_inset

 5-brane background.
 Each crossing of a solid line and the dashed one gives us an R-operator,
 which we call L-operator.
 Thus we conclude that the surface defect is represented in the lattice
 model by the insertion of a transfer matrix constructed from L-operators.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us consider the simplest interesting setup where we have just two D5-branes
 and a single D3-brane, and identify the concrete form of the transfer matrix
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:transferL"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 in this case.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $N=2$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(N,q\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(N,q+2\right)$
\end_inset

 5-branes are related by an SL(
\begin_inset Formula $2;\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

) transformation of type IIB string theory.
 Therefore, we can go to a duality frame in which the transfer matrix only
 involves either 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(N,0\right)$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(N,-1\right)$
\end_inset

 regions or 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(N,0\right)$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(N,1\right)$
\end_inset

 regions.
 The two cases are on an equal footing, and in fact related in a simple
 way, as we will see.
 We first consider the transfer matrix in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(N,-1\right)$
\end_inset

 background.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We denote the L-operator in this case by 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{\diamondsuit}$
\end_inset

 since it is the operator that arises when a dashed line is inserted in
 a brane tiling model described by the diamond quiver constructed from the
 R-operator (eq:diamond quiver).
 In the situation under consideration, the gauge group of a brane tiling
 model is a product of SU(2) groups, and the surface defect is labeled 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(R_{1},R_{2}\right)=\left(\emptyset,fund\right)$
\end_inset

; the D3-brane wraps the circle 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \zeta_{2}=0\right\} $
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{\diamondsuit}$
\end_inset

 be the space of meromorphic functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f(z)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $f(z)=f(1/z)$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $W=\mathbb{C}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Then we can represent 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{\diamondsuit}:W\otimes V^{\diamondsuit}\rightarrow V^{\diamondsuit}\otimes W$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times2$
\end_inset

 matrix whose entries are operators acting on functions in 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{\diamondsuit}$
\end_inset

.
 The R-matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{R}_{ij}^{\diamondsuit}:W_{i}\otimes W_{j}\rightarrow W_{j}\otimes W_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $4\times4$
\end_inset

 matrix.
 These operators, together with the R-operator 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{\diamondsuit}$
\end_inset

, satisfy the Yang-Baxter equations (4equations).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the other hand, in the context of integrable lattice models Sklyanin
 constructed an L-operator 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{\mathrm{S}}:W\otimes V^{\diamondsuit}\rightarrow V^{\diamondsuit}\otimes W$
\end_inset

 that solves the RLL relation [Sklyanin^2]
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{R}_{12}^{\mathrm{B}}\left(u_{1},u_{2}\right)L_{1}^{\mathrm{S}}\left(u_{1},\left(\nu,l\right)\right)L_{2}^{\mathrm{S}}\left(u_{2},\left(\nu,l\right)\right)=L_{2}^{\mathrm{S}}\left(u_{2},\left(\nu,l\right)\right)L_{1}^{\mathrm{S}}\left(u_{1},\left(\nu,l\right)\right)\mathcal{R}_{12}^{\mathrm{B}}\left(u_{1},u_{2}\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with Baxter's R-matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{R}_{ij}^{\mathrm{B}}:W_{i}\otimes W_{j}\rightarrow W_{j}\otimes W_{i}$
\end_inset

 for the eight-vertex model [Baxter^2].
 Here 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a complex spectral parameter for 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{i}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\nu,l\right)$
\end_inset

 is a pair of complex spectral parameters for 
\begin_inset Formula $V^{\diamondsuit}$
\end_inset

.
 Baxter's R-matrix solves the Yang-Baxter equation
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{R}_{12}^{\mathrm{B}}\left(u_{1},u_{2}\right)\mathcal{R}_{13}^{\mathrm{B}}\left(u_{1},u_{3}\right)\mathcal{R}_{23}^{\mathrm{B}}\left(u_{2},u_{3}\right)=\mathcal{R}_{23}^{\mathrm{B}}\left(u_{2},u_{3}\right)\mathcal{R}_{13}^{\mathrm{B}}\left(u_{1},u_{3}\right)\mathcal{R}_{12}^{\mathrm{B}}\left(u_{1},u_{2}\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 and the solution is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{R}_{ij}^{\mathrm{B}}\left(u_{i},u_{j}\right)=P\sum_{a=0}^{3}w_{a}\left(u_{i}-u_{j}\right)\sigma_{a}\otimes\sigma_{a},\quad\,w_{a}\left(u\right)=\frac{\theta_{a+1}\left(u+\eta\right)}{\theta_{a+1}\left(\eta\right)},
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $P:W_{i}\otimes W_{j}\rightarrow W_{j}\otimes W_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the permutation operator, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{a}$
\end_inset

 are the Pauli matrices and 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times2$
\end_inset

 unit matrix, 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{a+1}\left(u\right)=\theta_{a+1}\left(u|\tau\right)$
\end_inset

 are the Jacobi theta functions, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau,\,\eta$
\end_inset

 are complex parameters of the eight-vertex model.
 Sklyanin's L-operator is defined by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
L^{\mathrm{S}}\left(u,\left(\nu,l\right)\right)=P\sum_{a=0}^{3}w_{a}\left(u+\eta\right)\sigma_{a}\otimes\mathbf{S}_{a}^{(l)}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 The operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{S}_{a}^{(l)}$
\end_inset

 act on meromorphic functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f(\zeta)$
\end_inset

 as difference operators:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left(\mathbf{S}_{a}^{(l)}f\right)\left(\zeta\right)=i^{\delta_{a,0}}\frac{\theta_{a+1}\left(\eta\right)}{\theta_{a+1}\left(2\zeta\right)}\left(\theta_{a+1}\left(2\zeta-2\eta l\right)f(\zeta+\eta)-\theta_{a+1}\left(-2\zeta-2\eta l\right)f(\zeta-\eta)\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 They generate the so-called Sklyanin algebra [Sklyanin^2].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In [Derkachov-Spiridonov], Derkachov and Spiridonov constructed an R-operator
 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{ij}^{\mathrm{DS}}:V_{i}^{\diamondsuit}\otimes V_{j}^{\diamondsuit}\rightarrow V_{j}^{\diamondsuit}\otimes V_{i}^{\diamondsuit}$
\end_inset

 that satisfies the RLL relation
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
 & R_{12}^{\mathrm{DS}}\left(\left(\nu_{1},l_{1}\right),\left(\nu_{2},l_{2}\right)\right)L_{2}^{\mathrm{DS}}\left(u,\left(\nu_{2},l_{2}\right)\right)L_{1}^{\mathrm{DS}}\left(u,\left(\nu_{1},l_{1}\right)\right)\nonumber \\
 & =L_{1}^{\mathrm{DS}}\left(u,\left(\nu_{1},l_{1}\right)\right)L_{2}^{\mathrm{DS}}\left(u,\left(\nu_{2},l_{2}\right)\right)R_{12}^{\mathrm{DS}}\left(\left(\nu_{1},l_{1}\right),\left(\nu_{2},l_{2}\right)\right),
\end{align}

\end_inset

 The L-operator 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{\mathrm{DS}}:W\otimes V^{\diamondsuit}\rightarrow V^{\diamondsuit}\otimes W$
\end_inset

 is essentially Sklyanin's L-operator, differing only by an automorphism
 of the Sklyanin algebra:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
L^{\mathrm{DS}}\left(u,\left(\nu,l\right)\right)=\varphi\sigma_{3}L^{\mathrm{S}}\varphi^{-1},\quad\,\left(\varphi f\right)(\zeta):=\exp(\pi i\zeta^{2}/\eta)f(\zeta).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This L-operator also satisfies the RLL relation with Baxter's R-matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{R}^{\mathrm{B}}$
\end_inset

.
 At this point, what is important is that they show their R-operator 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{\mathrm{DS}}$
\end_inset

 is precisely the R-operator for the diamond quiver in the brane tiling
 model 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{\diamondsuit}$
\end_inset

, that is, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
R_{ij}^{\mathrm{DS}}\left(\left(\nu_{i},l_{i}\right),\left(\nu_{j},l_{j}\right)\right)=R_{ij}^{\diamondsuit}\left(\left(a_{i},b_{i}\right),\left(a_{j},b_{j}\right)\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 with the variables 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 are related by 
\begin_inset Formula $z=\exp(2\pi i\zeta)$
\end_inset

 and the parameters matched as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
a_{i}b_{i} & =\exp(-2\pi i\nu_{i}),\quad\,\frac{a_{i}}{b_{i}}=\exp(2\pi i\eta(2l_{i}+1)),\\
\left(p,q\right) & =\left(\exp(2\pi i\tau),\exp(4\pi i\eta)\right).
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Based on these observations, we propose that the L-operator for the diamond
 quiver 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
L^{\diamondsuit}\left(c,\left(a,b\right)\right)=
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 is the L-operator of Derkachov and Spiridonov:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
L^{\mathrm{DS}}\left(u,\left(\nu,l\right)\right)=L^{\diamondsuit}\left(c,\left(a,b\right)\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 Requiring 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{\diamondsuit}\left(c,\left(a,b\right)\right)=L^{\diamondsuit}\left(1,\left(a/c,b/c\right)\right)$
\end_inset

 fixes the relation between the two spectral parameters for the dashed line
 to be
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
c=\exp(\pi iu).
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the computation of the transfer matrix, we exploit the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{\diamondsuit}$
\end_inset

 really consists of three parts separated by zig-zag paths:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
L_{i}^{\diamondsuit}\left(c,\left(a_{i},b_{i}\right)\right)=.\label{eq:pieceL}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 Reflecting this structure, 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{\diamondsuit}$
\end_inset

 can be expressed in the following factorized form:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
L_{i}^{\diamondsuit}\left(c,\left(a_{i},b_{i}\right)\right)=B\left(z_{i};\frac{b_{i}}{c}\right)\cdot\varphi(z_{i})\frac{1}{\theta_{1}(z_{i}^{2})}\left(\begin{array}{cc}
\Delta_{i}^{1/2} & 0\\
0 & \Delta_{i}^{-1/2}
\end{array}\right)\varphi^{-1}(z_{i})\cdot A\left(z_{i};\frac{a_{i}}{c}\right).\label{eq:diamondL}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 In this expression, 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{i}^{\pm1/2}$
\end_inset

 are difference operators acting on functions of 
\begin_inset Formula $z_{i}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\Delta_{i}^{\pm1/2}f\right)(z_{i})=f(q^{\pm1/2}z_{i})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
A(z;a)=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
\bar{\theta}_{4}(a/z) & \bar{\theta}_{3}(a/z)\\
\bar{\theta}_{4}(az) & \bar{\theta}_{3}(az)
\end{array}\right),\quad\,B(z;b)=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
\bar{\theta}_{3}(bz) & -\bar{\theta}_{3}(b/z)\\
\bar{\theta}_{4}(bz) & -\bar{\theta}_{4}(b/z)
\end{array}\right),
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\theta}_{a}(z)=\theta_{a}(z;\sqrt{p})$
\end_inset

 and we used the multiplicative notation for the theta functions.
 Roughly speaking, one can think of the three matrices in the expression
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:diamondL"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 as corresponding to the left, middle and right parts of the above diagram.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The transfer matrix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:transferL"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is obtained by concatenating 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 copies of the pieces 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:pieceL"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 along a loop: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
concatenate.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 Thus, multiplying 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 copies of the L-operators 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:diamondL"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and using formulas in the appendix, we obtain the following formula for
 the transfer matrix:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
 & \mathrm{Tr}_{W}\left(L_{n}^{\diamondsuit}\left(c,\left(a_{n},b_{n}\right)\right)\circ_{W}\cdots\circ_{W}L_{1}^{\diamondsuit}\left(c,\left(a_{1},b_{1}\right)\right)\right)\nonumber \\
 & =\sum_{s_{1}=\pm1}\cdots\sum_{s_{n}=\pm1}\prod_{i=1}^{n}\ell\left(z_{i-1}^{s_{i-1}},z_{i}^{s_{i}};\frac{b_{i-1}}{c},\frac{a_{i}}{c}\right)\prod_{j=1}^{n}\Delta_{j}^{s_{j}/2},\label{eq:proposal}
\end{align}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\ell\left(w,z;b,a\right)=\frac{1}{\theta(z^{2})}\theta\left(\sqrt{\frac{p}{q}}ba\frac{w}{z}\right)\theta\left(\sqrt{\frac{p}{q}}\frac{a}{b}\frac{1}{wz}\right).
\end{equation}

\end_inset

In this formula we have dropped off an overall constant independent of the
 spectral parameters.
 At any rate, the overall normalization of the L-operators cannot be determined
 by the RLL relations.
 The RLL relations actually admit more degrees of freedom than just the
 overall normalization.
 For example, we can multiply 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{\diamondsuit}\left(c,\left(a,b\right)\right)$
\end_inset

 by a function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(c,(a,b))$
\end_inset

 of its spectral parameters, and the new one still solves the RLL relations.
 In the next subsection we will check the proposal by comparing it with
 independent computations from gauge theory.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So far we have considered the surface defect labeled 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(R_{1},R_{2}\right)=\left(\emptyset,fund\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Of course, we may also consider the case with 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(R_{1},R_{2}\right)=\left(fund,\emptyset\right)$
\end_inset

