\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=2$
\end_inset

 linear quiver theory is obtained by compactification of the 6d 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=\left(2,0\right)$
\end_inset

 theory of type 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{N-1}$
\end_inset

 on a cylinder with 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 punctures, or a sphere with 
\begin_inset Formula $m+2$
\end_inset

 punctures.
 We distinguish the two punctures coming from the ends of the cylinder from
 the 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 punctures in between.
 They are referred to as maximal and minimal punctures, respectively.
 In the class-
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

 language, the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=2$
\end_inset

 linear quiver theory is a theory associated to a sphere with 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 maximal and 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 minimal punctures, see figure.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
R-symmetry of the theory is 
\begin_inset Formula $SU(2)_{I}\times U(1)_{r}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $SU(2)_{I}$
\end_inset

 represents the rotation symmetry of the 789-space, and 
\begin_inset Formula $U(1)_{r}$
\end_inset

 the rotation symmetry of the 45-plane.
 The SU(N) flavor node from each end of the quiver is associated to the
 maximal puncture on the corresponding side of the sphere.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th gauge node is associated to the tube between the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th and 
\begin_inset Formula $(i+1)$
\end_inset

th minimal punctures.
 To the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th minimal puncture is associated a flavor symmetry 
\begin_inset Formula $U(1)_{i}$
\end_inset

 which acts on the hypermultiplet charged under the 
\begin_inset Formula $(i-1)$
\end_inset

th and 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th gauge nodes.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Following the philosophy of class-
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

 theories, we decompose this theory into basic building blocks by decoupling
 gauge fields.
 Roughly, the gauge coupling of the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th gauge node is inversely proportional to the length between the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th and 
\begin_inset Formula $(i+1)$
\end_inset

th minimal punctures.
 To make the gauge couplings small, we take the minimal punctures far apart
 from one another.
 Then the surface looks like a string of 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 spheres, each containing a single minimal puncture, connected by long tubes.
 The smaller the gauge couplings get, the longer the tubes become, and eventuall
y these spheres split up as the couplings go to zero.
 Each of the spheres represents a bifundamental hypermultiplet, which is
 a linear quiver with 
\begin_inset Formula $m=1$
\end_inset

, so it has one minimal and two maximal punctures.
 The quiver thus breaks into a collection of three-punctured spheres, or
 trinions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Conversely, a sphere with two maximal and 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 minimal punctures is obtained by gluing 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 trinions together, namely by replacing pairs of maximal punctures with
 tubes.
 In general, we can connect two Riemann surfaces with a tube at maximal
 punctures.
 From the point of view of gauge theory, gluing corresponds to gauging the
 diagonal combination of the SU(N) flavor symmetries associated to the maximal
 punctures involved.
 Using trinions with one minimal and two maximal punctures, we can obtain
 any linear quiver in this way, and for that manner also a circular quiver
 by further gluing the two ends of a linear quiver together.
 In this sense, these trinions are building blocks for linear and circular
 quivers.
 As these two kinds of quivers can be treated essentially in the same manner,
 we will focus on linear quivers in the followings.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To make contact with brane tilings, what we need to do is to find the counterpar
t of trinion, building block of quiver gauge theories, in brane tiling systems.
 To do this, we describe the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=2$
\end_inset

 linear quiver theory as an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=1$
\end_inset

 quiver gauge theory.
 In terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=1$
\end_inset

 supermultiplets, the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}=2$
\end_inset

 vector multiplet for the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th gauge node decomposes into a vector multiplet and a chiral multiplet
 
\begin_inset Formula $\Phi_{i}$
\end_inset

 in the adjoint representation with 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(r,I_{3}\right)=\left(-1,0\right)$
\end_inset

, while the 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

th hypermultiplet consists of two bifundamental chiral multiplets 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{i},\,\tilde{Q}_{i}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(r,I_{3}\right)=\left(0,1/2\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Here 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{3}$
\end_inset

 is a Cartan generator of 
\begin_inset Formula $SU(2)_{I}$
\end_inset

.
 The pair 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(Q_{i},\tilde{Q}_{i}^{\dagger}\right)$
\end_inset

 transforms in the doublet of 
\begin_inset Formula $SU(2)_{I}$
\end_inset

 and have 
\begin_inset Formula $U(1)_{i}$
